1.6	Five-Year Accident History

In the past five years of operation, a single incident occurred at the PXP Inglewood Gas Plant.  The incident occurred on August 13, 1999 and involved a broken pipe nipple resulting in the release of NGL vapor.  The incident resulted from a crane which accidentally swung in the vicinity of the pipe.  Once vessel pressure was reduced, the broken segment of pipe was removed, and a new valve was installed.  

1.7	Emergency Response Program Summary

PXP has developed written emergency response procedures to address all elements that may be encountered during planning, responding or following up to an emergency at the Inglewoo

d facility.  Application of the emergency response procedures ensures compliance with OSHA Standard 29 CFR 1910.38 (Emergency Response Plans) and the emergency response element of the PSM.  The basic concept of PXP¿s emergency procedures are to provide a comprehensive approach for managing emergencies.  The four elements of this approach are prevention, preparedness, response, and recovery.

The Emergency Response Action Plan (ERAP) is designed to be applicable to any type of emergency that may affect PXP and based on the concept that the elements of emergency response are similar, regardless of the hazard.  It contains pages from the Integrated Contingency Plan (ICP).  The ERAP contains the following sections:

1. Facility Information;
2. Notifications;
3. Initial Response Actions;
4. Evacuation Plans/Emergency Shutdown Procedures;
5. Oil Pipeline Route; and
6. Ballona Creek Boom and Staging Locations.


1.9	Planned Changes to Improve Safety

PXP enforces continuous improvements to safety and health and tracks training to ensure commitment to safe working practices and the protection of the employees and the environment.

PXP is maintaining documentation on its safety, inspection, training, and MOC programs, using the forms provided in the appendix of the Process Safety Management (PSM) document.  The documentation provides a history and upkeep of the programs, thus better ensuring their effectiveness.  Finally, because the PSM manual is maintained as a living document, its continuing updating provides a means of sustaining its original objective to improve the health and safety of individuals associated with the ammonia process.
